    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-12-23T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-12-23T05:00:00-05:00" n="278"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d278">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.611/231: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_WJC1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-12-23T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 23, 1934—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>423. Department’s 305, December 18, 2 p.m. As stated in Embassy’s 332, September
                    27, 4 p.m.,<note n="78" xml:id="d278fn78">Not printed.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MVI1">Mezhlauk</persName> promised to have assurances
                    desired by the Department in the shortest possible time. These promises were
                    reiterated personally to Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BWC1"
                        >Bullitt</persName> on October 8th prior to his departure. Subsequent
                    communications with <persName corresp="#p_MVI1">Mezhlauk</persName>’s office
                    failed to produce more than assurances that the desired information would be
                    forthcoming shortly. On November 29th <persName corresp="#p_MVI1"
                        >Mezhlauk</persName>’s secretary informed the Embassy that any further
                    inquiries should be made of the Foreign Office as <persName corresp="#p_MVI1"
                        >Mezhlauk</persName> had turned the entire matter over to it. A full report
                    of the situation was forwarded to the Department by despatch No. 277, December
                        3rd.<note n="78" xml:id="d278fn79">Not printed.</note> As it was on the
                    advice of <persName corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinov</persName> and other Soviet
                    officials that the Ambassador approached <persName corresp="#p_MVI1"
                        >Mezhlauk</persName> as the one Soviet official competent to handle the
                    matter with the maximum of efficiency and authority the sudden decision to place
                    it in the hands of the Foreign Office implies <pb facs="0376" n="270"
                        xml:id="pg_270"/> not only failure by <persName corresp="#p_MVI1"
                        >Mezhlauk</persName> and others to carry out promises to the Ambassador but
                    will make it most difficult to obtain effective action. With this in view I have
                    considered it advisable to await the Department’s instructions before
                    establishing the precedent of dealing through the Foreign Office on the
                    questions relating particularly to costs of local labor, transportation and
                    materials.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
